title: For Trade:  Winchester Model 55
postcontent: Winchester Model 55 single-shot rifle. .22 caliber, an "automatic single-shot"...that is to say that after cocking, a single cartridge is hand loaded through the top port and upon firing the empty case is ejected through the bottom port and the action is recocked. When another shell is pushed down through the gate for loading, the safety automatically resets. The barrel measures 21-3/4" in length and is fitted with iron sights. The walnut stock is in very nice has not been sanded or refinished. The mechanics are in good working order and the bore is excellent. These were made in somewhat limited numbers between 1958-1961...a strange concept that was probably doomed from the start...but an interesting and collectible Winchester rifle.

postcontent: This is a Mossberg Model 90048 fully rifled slug barrel made for the Remington Wingmaster/870. 24 inches, highly polished Wingmaster-grade, full-gloss bluing (not the Remington 870 Express matte finish). Williams folding leaf rear sight and fine brass bead on ramp front sight. Magnum 3-inch chamber and 1:36 twist.I bought this barrel new, sighted it in, and used it for one season before going to a dedicated rifled slug gun. This barrel has very few rounds through it--essentially, just what I put through it to find the ammo it liked best. That ammo is Brenneke standard 2.75" sabots, which it will throw consistently in 3-inch groups at 75 yards. With the 1:36 twist rate, I found it is best suited to heavier, moderate-velocity ammo--like the Brennekes. If you've ever shot slugs out of a relatively light gun like an 870, you'll probably agree that you'll want to forego the magnum or high-velocity loads if you want to be able to get any kind of followup shot. But if you're not bothered by recoil, that 3-inch magnum capability is there for you.This barrel is in like-new shape: mirror bore, no rust inside or out, bluing easily 98%. It's time for this barrel to get out of my safe and onto your gun; it's all set to mount up on your Wingmaster or 870 and go to work. title: For Sale:  Springfield Range Officer Lightweight Champion 9mm
postcontent:
I've shot approximately 200 rounds through this, so it's barely broken in. It's missing the OEM holster, which sucked anyway, but everything else that came with the gun is included (mags, different colored pipes, tools, etc). Here's more info:
Mfg P/N: PI9137LP
FAMILY: 1911 Style Pistol Series
MODEL: 1911 RO Champion LW
TYPE: Semi-Auto Pistol
ACTION: Dual Spring w/ Full Length Guide Rod
FINISH: Stainless
FRAME: Forged Lightweight Alloy
STOCK/GRIPS: Thinline Cocobolo Hardwood
CALIBER/GAUGE: 9mm
CAPACITY: 2 - 9+1
# OF MAGS: 2
MAGAZINE DESC: 2 - 9 rd.
BARREL: 4"
OVERALL LENGTH: 7.5"
SIGHTS: Fiber Optic Front & Low-Profile Combat Rear
SLIDE: Forged Carbon Steel
The Range Officer Champion is a perfect fit for those looking for a concealable 1911 that won't weigh them down. While a normal, all steel 1911 can weigh over two and a half pounds empty, the 9mm Champion tips the scales at just 31.5 ounces. The .45ACP model weighs in even less at just 30 ounces, thanks to the bigger hole in the barrel. That's quite a difference when it's on the hip all day.
While the overall height is the same as that of the Range Officer Operator, the Championâ„¢ includes a four inch stainless steel match grade barrel as opposed to the Government size five inch barrel. In the Champion, we use a bull barrel fitted to the slide that houses a supported ramp to save wear and tear on the frame over time. As a result, we can use lighter weight forged aluminum for the frame. That helps us shave weight for its intended carry mission.
The sights are all business, with a fiber optic up front and a low profile combat sight in the rear that won't snag during the draw. For recoil control and function, we use a dual-spring assembly that allows us to control precisely the recoil impulse in this smaller package, thereby ensuring reliable function with a minimum of fuss to the shooter.
The Range Officer Champion is available in 9mm and .45ACP. Both models ship with two magazines, seven rounds each for the .45ACP and nine rounds for the 9MM. Even though the Range Officer® Champion is smaller and lighter, you won' t have to sacrifice capacity for carry convenience.
